# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Easiest path — zero manual secrets: `npm run up` (or `sh scripts/up.sh`)
# generates strong values for the three secrets below into .env on first run,
# then starts the stack. It never overwrites a value you've already set.
#
# Local development: `npm run docker:dev` supplies safe defaults (loopback-only
# ports + dev secrets) via docker-compose.dev.yml — copy nothing.
#
# Production (`docker compose up` / `npm run docker:prod` / Coolify): the base
# compose has NO secret defaults, so you MUST set these (use `npm run up`, a
# .env file, or your platform's env). Postgres and the sandbox-controller are
# not published to the host — only the platform port is.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Postgres password (compose builds DATABASE_URL from it). Required in prod.
# POSTGRES_PASSWORD=

# Shared secret between the platform and the sandbox-controller. The controller
# has Docker-socket (root-equivalent) access and REFUSES TO BOOT without a
# non-default value in production. Generate with: openssl rand -hex 32
# CONTROLLER_SECRET=

# Root of trust for encrypting provider API keys at rest. MUST be set in
# production: it lives OUTSIDE the database, so a DB leak alone cannot decrypt
# stored secrets. Must be 64 hex characters. Generate with: openssl rand -hex 32
# If unset, production REFUSES TO BOOT (fail-closed). In dev — or in prod with
# ALLOW_DB_MASTER_KEY=true — Capka falls back to an insecure DB-stored key.
# CAPKA_MASTER_KEY=

# OPTIONAL hardening for the first-run setup wizard. Leave it UNSET for a normal
# install — first-run is frictionless and whoever runs setup becomes admin. Set
# it for a public, internet-reachable deploy where a stranger might race you to
# the setup page: then claiming the admin account requires this token, which the
# wizard reads from a #token=… setup link (printed by scripts/up.sh when set) or
# you paste once. Generate with: openssl rand -hex 32
# SETUP_TOKEN=

# Only needed when running the app OUTSIDE docker-compose (which auto-configures
# it). Example: postgresql://Capka:PASSWORD@localhost:5432/Capka
# DATABASE_URL=

# Public origin of the app (scheme + host, no trailing slash). Optional: if
# unset, Capka derives it per-request from proxy headers (X-Forwarded-Proto /
# Host), so localhost and most reverse proxies work with no config. Set it
# explicitly in production behind a proxy — it's the non-spoofable source of
# truth for auth callbacks and absolute links. Example: https://capka.example.com
# PUBLIC_URL=

# Sandbox isolation runtime. Default `runc` — standard Docker isolation; boots on
# any host with no extra setup. For UNTRUSTED or MULTI-TENANT code, opt into
# gVisor: install it on the host (`sudo sh scripts/install-gvisor.sh`) and set this
# to `runsc`. The secure profile is then FAIL-CLOSED — the controller refuses to
# boot if gVisor isn't registered on the daemon (it never silently downgrades), so
# leave this at `runc` unless you've installed gVisor. See the README section
# "gVisor (opt-in hardening)".
# SANDBOX_RUNTIME=runc

# Sandbox internet access is normally managed in the admin panel (Security →
# Internet access). This env flag is the deployment-level gate; it defaults to
# true. Set it to false to hard-forbid sandbox egress regardless of the in-app
# toggle (for untrusted/multi-tenant deployments).
# SANDBOX_ALLOW_NETWORK=true

# Host folder mounts: when the admin enables folder access (Settings, off by
# default), the agent can bind-mount SERVER folders into its sandbox. This
# optional perimeter restricts which host paths are mountable to subpaths of the
# listed roots (colon-separated), on top of the built-in system-path denylist.
# Unset → any non-system path is allowed, with the admin confirmation as the gate.
# Recommended for multi-admin deployments. See SECURITY.md "Host folder mounts".
# SANDBOX_MOUNT_ALLOW=/srv/shared:/mnt/nas

# Pin the Capka image version (platform/controller/sandbox) for deliberate
# upgrades. Unset → `latest`. Set to a published release tag, e.g. v0.2.0, then
# `docker compose pull && docker compose up -d` to upgrade. See docs/UPGRADE.md.
# CAPKA_VERSION=

# Host port the platform is published on (container port is always 3000). Change
# it only if another app on this box already uses 3000; then point your domain
# routing at the new port. Unset → 3000.
# PLATFORM_PORT=3000

# Interface the platform port binds to. Default 0.0.0.0 (all interfaces) so it
# works out of the box. Set 127.0.0.1 to bind loopback-only when a reverse proxy
# fronts the app (the proxy reaches it via localhost) — recommended on hosts
# where Docker publishes past the firewall (UFW).
# PLATFORM_BIND=0.0.0.0

# ── Sandbox tuning (optional; sane defaults shown) ──────────────────────────
# Per-sandbox RAM in MB. The sandbox /tmp + /opt/mcp tmpfs are charged to this
# same cgroup, so keep headroom above what the code needs.
# SANDBOX_MEMORY_MB=1024
# Maximum processes/threads per sandbox. gVisor consumes part of this budget;
# values below 128 can break image/document rendering. Default: 256.
# SANDBOX_PIDS_LIMIT=256
# Max concurrent sandboxes (running containers) per user.
# MAX_SESSIONS_PER_USER=2
# Idle time before a sandbox CONTAINER is stopped (files + workspace row survive,
# revived on the next tool call). Milliseconds. Default 15 min.
# SANDBOX_IDLE_TTL_MS=900000
# How long a WORKSPACE may go unused before its files are deleted (row + disk) —
# the real "how long do my files live" knob. Milliseconds. Default 30 days.
# WORKSPACE_TTL_MS=2592000000
# Grace for TRULY orphaned dirs (no DB row) before the sweep removes them.
# Milliseconds. Default 7 days.
# GC_GRACE_MS=604800000

# Turnkey HTTPS: set DOMAIN and `npm run up` brings the stack up behind Caddy
# with an automatic Let's Encrypt cert. Requires public DNS for DOMAIN pointing
# at this host and ports 80+443 free. Example:
# DOMAIN=capka.example.com

# OPTIONAL ACME account email. When set (only relevant with DOMAIN), Caddy also
# enables ZeroSSL as a fallback certificate issuer — useful because the free
# <ip>.sslip.io hostnames share one Let's Encrypt rate limit that can be briefly
# exhausted. Unset ⇒ Let's Encrypt only. Example:
# ACME_EMAIL=you@example.com
# NOTE: the install scripts (up.sh) turn this into Caddy config. On a plain
# `docker compose up` or Coolify deploy, set it by writing the line yourself:
#   mkdir -p data/caddy/conf.d && echo 'email you@example.com' > data/caddy/conf.d/email.caddy

# OPTIONAL host Docker socket path for the socket-proxy bind. Leave unset for a
# normal (rootful) daemon. Set it for ROOTLESS Docker, whose socket lives under
# your user runtime dir — otherwise the sandbox controller can't reach Docker.
# See SECURITY.md. Example:
# DOCKER_SOCKET=/run/user/1000/docker.sock
